	<td class="bodycopy">
		<!--DESIGN CREDITS BEGIN HERE-->
<!-- a href=mailto:bjc@stevensons.co.nz -->
Hi mate. I just got a turn result in one of my current Payola games.
<P>
I just wanted to let you know what I've been doing for the last 20
minutes here at work.
<P>
I've been sitting here looking at the map, grinning from ear to ear. Not
because I'm doing well - although I'm not doing badly - but because I'm
sitting here thinking about all the permutations and trying to figure
out what are the most important moves. It's brilliant, mate. That is what
is so special about Diplomacy - working out what is likely to happen,
and then working out which of your moves are the most vital. Lots of
people talk about coin tosses when faced with 50-50 guesses. I find
it's only very rarely a coin toss. One of the options, if it doesn't
work, will leave you more exposed than the other as often as not.
However, as we all know, the trick doesn't stop there. You have to figure
out how astute your oponent(s) is(are), and nut out whether they'll play
for you covering the least risky option.
<P>
What I <u>love</u> about Payola so much is that it's taken that wonderful part
of Diplomacy, and amplified it - there's even more permutations, more what
if's, and that second level of deception.
<P>
Every single time I get a Payola result, Manus, I sit there for around fifteen
minutes with this huge grin on my face - a grin that is in appreciation
of the wonderful creation you've given us - a grin born out of
appreciation not for how well I'm doing, but for the beauty of Payola.
<P>
Thanks, mate. Few things in life make me feel as good as Payola - even
when I'm losing. I hate variants. I'm renowned for my dislike of them,
but there's an exception to every rule, and you've built us all a
wonderful exception.

	</td>
	</tr>
