	<tr valign=top>
	<td class="bodycopy">

<!-- a href=mailto:stanley.szeto@levershirt.com -->
More so than any other Diplomacy variant, Payola requires you to get into
the mind of your opponents.  You can psyche others into over-paying, or
you can create a false sense of calm and complacency, allowing you to execute
a lightning strike when the timing is right.  Also, not all moves are equal,
and it satisfies like a good bargain when your cheap payoff bounces an
expensive unit bribed by your opponent.  On the other hand, it feels like
a tidal wave crushing over your head when a rich opponent flattens you with
bribes that exceed your annual pay.  All you can do is sit back, watch in
awe and disbelief, and admire the strength and power of the steamroller.
<p>
Payola is a fascinating variant.  It has become the
only form of Diplomacy I play!
<p>
The main skill in Payola is correctly gauging how much it costs to to
control each unit on the board.  When a certain move is a prerequisite for
another one, this first move's importance increases and so does its value.
Coping with these changes adds much complexity and fun to the overall
challenge.
<P>
For example, let's say England is threatening Norway with its North Sea
fleet.  A mediocre Payola Russian player may try to bribe heavily for
England's fleet to turn away.  A stronger Payola player may gamble that
England will convoy its army across from Yorkshire, and therefore try to
bribe that army rather than the fleet away, since the army will be much
cheaper to bribe.  Not only is England kept off Norway, Russia gains a
financial advantage because it spent less money bribing the Yorkshire army
than England spent on its North Sea fleet.  Understanding and taking
advantage of these dynamics is what differentiates the better Payola player
from the mediocre one.
	</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


